<HEADLINE>
<P>
TIMES HONORS TOP PREP CAGERS, OUTSTANDING COACHES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ROB FERNAS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Centers Ed Stokes of St. Bernard and Lisa Leslie of Morningside and coaches 
Carl Strong of Torrance and Frank Scott of Morningside were the South Bay award 
winners Sunday at The Times high school basketball banquet at the Anaheim 
Hilton. 
</P>
<P>
Stokes and Leslie were named players of the year while Strong and Scott were 
selected boys and girls coaches of the year. Scott, who guided the Lady 
Monarchs to the state Division I title, won the award for the second straight 
year. 
</P>
<P>
Stokes, a 6-11 senior, averaged 25 points, 15 rebounds and four blocked shots a 
game to lead St. Bernard to a 23-6 record, the Camino Real League title and the 
second round of the Southern Section 5-AA playoffs. His previous honors include 
Camino Real League most valuable player and Southern Section Division I player 
of the year. He has signed to play for Coach Lute Olson at Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
Torrance was picked by coaches to finish last in the Bay League, but under 
Strong the Tartars surprised everyone by contending for the title until the 
last week of the season. They finished third and won two games in the Southern 
Section 4-AA playoffs before losing to eventual champion San Bernardino in the 
quarterfinals. Torrance finished with a 16-11 record. 
</P>
<P>
The 6-5 Leslie established herself as the most dominant girls player in the 
state and perhaps the nation by leading Morningside to a 32-1 record and its 
first state title. The junior averaged 26 points, 14.6 rebounds and nearly 
seven blocked shots as the Lady Monarchs rose to the nation's No. 2 ranking in 
USA Today. Leslie was named to the Parade All-American first team. 
</P>
<P>
Scott guided the Morningside girls to their best season ever. They repeated as 
Southern Section and regional champions before avenging last year's one-point 
loss to Fremont of Oakland in the state Division I final, 60-50. Scott did it 
with a team that had only one senior -- point guard JoJo Witherspoon -- and 
started two sophomores and one freshman. ROB FERNAS 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Tartars' Coach Carl Strong Los Angeles Times; Photo, St. Bernard's Ed 
Stokes ; Photo, Morningside's Lisa Leslie ; Photo, Monarchs' Coach Frank Scott 
</P>
