<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: RADIO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALEENE MacMINN, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Garrison Keillor will make his first Los Angeles appearance in seven years June 
9-10 in the "Third Annual Farewell Performance" of his "A Prairie Home 
Companion." The local dates at Universal Amphitheater will cap a 13-city tour 
that includes a stop June 6 in San Diego's Symphony Hall. The June 10 show here 
will be broadcast live on American Public Radio (locally on KUSC-FM, 91.5). 
Keillor, who quit his popular weekly radio variety program two years ago in 
favor of a writing career, has continued to spoof his departure from the 
airwaves with annual "farewell" programs. Last year, the second annual farewell 
show emanated live from Radio City in New York. Keillor says he decided to do 
the third annual farewell about a year ago, "a couple of months before the 
second annual. I was afraid if I waited for people to beg me to do it, they 
might not. It's a good rule in show business not to wait in the wings too long 
before you come out to do an encore."ALEENE MacMINN 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA040689-0039 </DOCNO>
