<HEADLINE>
<P>
AVIATION FIRM PLEADS GUILTY IN IMPORT BAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the first prosecution under a 1986 anti-apartheid law, an aviation company 
and its chairman pleaded guilty Wednesday to importing four jet engines that 
were owned by South African Airways. 
</P>
<P>
Air Ground Equipment Sales Inc. of West Babylon, N.Y., and its chairman, Robert 
Fessler, had been indicted Monday. The guilty pleas were part of an agreement 
with federal prosecutors, who said the case was the first prosecution under the 
Comprehensive Anti-Apartheid Act of 1986. Fessler faces up to 10 years in 
prison and a $250,000 fine. 
</P>
<P>
Fessler told U.S. District Judge Mark A. Costantino of Brooklyn that he had 
been negotiating to buy the engines from South African Airways before the law 
was enacted. The company went ahead with the purchase and shipped the engines 
to Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
