<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST: LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
VICTIM WAS BACKING AWAY, WITNESS SAYS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Malik Smith, son of actress Beverly Todd and television director Kris Kaiser, 
was backing away from an argument at a Salt Lake City disco when accused 
assailant John Leota threw the punch that killed him, a prosecution witness 
testified Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
Smith, 18, who lived in Los Angeles and was on a ski vacation, died two days 
after the encounter. Preliminary hearings are being held to decide whether 
Leota, who is charged with second-degree murder, should stand trial. 
</P>
<P>
Chris Foote said he was at Club 35, a West Valley disco, the night of March 18 
and saw Leota, also 18, strike Smith. 
</P>
<P>
Foote said that when Leota hit Smith, the punch "lifted him six inches off the 
floor." 
</P>
<P>
Before he was hit, it appeared Smith was stepping backward away from an 
argument with Leota, Foote added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
