<HEADLINE>
<P>
NIBBLES AND BITS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Irvine's new Backstage Theatre &amp; Co. will open its doors for the first time 
this weekend -- not with a show but with two seminars on breaking into the 
entertainment industry (10 a.m to 2 p.m. on Saturday; 11 a.m.to 3 p.m. on 
Sunday). Actors Paul Kreppel (from TV's "It's a Living") and Danielle Brisebois 
(late of "Archie Bunker's Place") and Bobby Hoffman of ABC casting ("General 
Hospital" and other shows) will be there, said Backstage co-founder Al 
Valletta. At 2691 Richter Ave., Suite 105. Admission: $50 for parent and child 
for Saturday's session; $15 for each additional family member; $75 on Sunday, 
adults only. For information: (714) 474-0792. 
</P>
<P>
Two international music and dance events are slated for June at the Orange 
County Performing Arts Center in Costa Mesa. Northern Indian sitarist Ravi 
Shankar will make his first Orange County appearance at 8 p.m. on June 2, under 
the sponsorship of the Orange County Historical and Cultural Foundation. The 
65-member Imperial Bells of China will appear at 8 p.m. on June 3 and at 2 p.m. 
on June 4. The troupe, from Hubei Province, will present music and dances of 
the "Warring States" period in China, 475-221 BC, using replicas of bells and 
other 2,400-year-old instruments. Information: (714) 556-7287. 
</P>
</TEXT>
