<HEADLINE>
<P>
WHAT THE POLICE ARE PACKING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Clipboard researched by Kathie Bozanich, Susan Davis Greene and Dallas 
Jamison / Los Angeles Times; Graphics by Doris Shields / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The attempts to ban so-called assault rifles is just the latest in a series of 
controversies involving firearms. Police officers have complained, for example, 
that they are being outgunned. And while no one can be sure what the bad guys 
are packing, Orange County police officers have several alternatives. The 
following list shows the official sidearm issued for individual officers, what 
is carried in patrol cars and the hardware used by special units such as SWAT 
teams: 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
ANAHEIM 
</P>
<P>
Individual officer issue: Smith &amp; Wesson .38- or .45-caliber revolver, 
9-millimeter semiautomatic or .45-caliber semiautomatic pistol. City issues the 
weapon. 
</P>
<P>
Patrol car: Remington 870 12-gauge shotgun. 
</P>
<P>
Special unit: Automatic assault rifles; high-powered sniper rifles; Heckler 
&amp; Koch MP-5 rifles. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
BREA 
</P>
<P>
Individual officer issue: Smith &amp; Wesson .38 or .45 revolver or .45 
semiautomatic pistol. City issues the weapon. 
</P>
<P>
Patrol car: Remington 870 shotgun. 
</P>
<P>
Special unit: Remington 870 laser-aimed shotguns and Ruger mini-14 carbines. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
BUENA PARK 
</P>
<P>
