<HEADLINE>
<P>
FIRST INTERSTATE JOINS OPEN-SATURDAY CLUB 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DOUGLAS FRANTZ, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
First Interstate Bank joined the herd Wednesday, announcing that its 321 
branches statewide will be open on Saturdays, beginning in May. 
</P>
<P>
The Los Angeles-based bank was the last of the state's five biggest banks to 
decide to open its branches on Saturdays. The hours will be from 9 a.m. to 1 
p.m. and the branches will offer full services. 
</P>
<P>
Within the past week, Bank of America, Security Pacific, Wells Fargo and Union 
Bank all have announced plans to open their branches on Saturdays, beginning 
April 15. 
</P>
<P>
First Interstate said its move to Saturdays was in response to customer surveys 
and to the decision by the other big California banks to increase their 
business hours. Many smaller independent banks have maintained Saturday hours 
for years. 
</P>
<P>
First Interstate said additional branch employees may be hired, but that staff 
costs are not expected to increase significantly. First Interstate is in the 
midst of a companywide cost-cutting campaign. 
</P>
<P>
While the other four banks also have extended their weekday hours, First 
Interstate did not and will continue to be open from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. Monday 
through Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
BUSINESS HOURS; BANKING INDUSTRY -- CALIFORNIA; WORKING HOURS; FIRST INTERSTATE 
