<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: RETAILING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARY ANN GALANTE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Three D Departments Inc. is getting out of stores it doesn't own. 
</P>
<P>
The Irvine-based retailer, which owns and operates the Three D Bed &amp; Bath 
chain, has also been leasing space in department stores for several years and 
currently operates linen and domestics departments in seven Van Leunens stores 
in Kentucky and Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
But it has agreed to sell Van Leunens the inventory, furniture and fixtures of 
those departments. Terms of the sale were not disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
Three D does not anticipate any gain or loss on the sale, the company said. 
Sales in the seven leased departments amounted to about 6% of Three D's sales 
of $34.9 million in fiscal 1988, ended July 30. Net income after tax totaled 
$719,000 in fiscal 1988. 
</P>
<P>
With the sale, Three D will no longer lease any departments in stores that it 
does not own, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
Three D Departments Inc. stock is traded on the American Stock Exchange. MARY 
ANN GALANTE 
</P>
</TEXT>
