<HEADLINE>
<P>
LOCAL; 
</P>
<P>
OWNER GETS 100 DAYS IN SLUM HOTEL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and wire service reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The longest house arrest to date for a Los Angeles slumlord was imposed today 
on the owner of the Palms Wilshire Hotel, who was sentenced to spend 100 days 
in his own dilapidated building. 
</P>
<P>
Amiya K. Goswami, 54, of Long Beach was ordered by Municipal Judge Suzanne 
Person to surrender next Thursday to begin serving the house arrest in a room 
at the four-story, 197-unit residential hotel at 626 S. Alvarado St. 
</P>
<P>
"Goswami has virtually ignored his legal responsibilities to maintain this 
hotel for over a year and half, and now the time has come for him to begin 
paying the price for that neglect and indifference," City Atty. James K. Hahn 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
