<HEADLINE>
<P>
IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
SPORTS AGENTS' CASE GOES TO JURY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
CHICAGO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The federal trial of sports agents Norby Walters and Lloyd Bloom went to a jury 
today. The two are accused of defrauding six universities by signing their 
scholarship football players as clients, and of threatening some players. 
</P>
<P>
In his closing statement to jurors Wednesday, defense attorney Dan Webb implied 
that the real villains were student athletes who signed contracts that violated 
NCAA rules and the schools themselves. U.S. Atty. Anton Valukas, in his closing 
statement, maligned Webb's tactics and argued that the sports agents knowingly 
cheated six universities out of scholarship money. 
</P>
<P>
Walters, 58, and Bloom, 29, were charged with mail fraud, conspiracy to commit 
fraud and racketeering. They were accused of luring dozens of college athletes 
with cash and other gifts to sign contracts in violation of NCAA rules, then 
using threats to keep their clients from reneging on the agreements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
